Here is the complete "Project Source" for this scenario, organized into the two files you need to recreate this setup from scratch.

1. The Secret Manifest (db-secret.yaml)

This file defines the sensitive data. Note that in a real YAML file, these values must be base64 encoded.

YAML
apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata:
  name: db-cred
type: Opaque
data:
  # Echo -n "admin" | base64
  db_user: YWRtaW4=
  # Echo -n "pass1234" | base64
  db_pass: cGFzczEyMzQ=
2. The Pod Manifest (sec-pod.yaml)

This file consumes the secret keys and maps them to custom environment variable names.

YAML
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: my-pod-secret-mount
  labels:
    app: prod
spec:
  containers:
    - name: my-cont
      image: busybox
      # We use /bin/sh because busybox does not have bash
      command: ["/bin/sh", "-c", "env | grep sec_generic && sleep 3600"]
      env:
        - name: sec_generic_1234
          valueFrom:
            secretKeyRef:
              name: db-cred
              key: db_user
        - name: sec_generic_4567
          valueFrom:
            secretKeyRef:
              name: db-cred
              key: db_pass
  restartPolicy: Always
Deployment Steps

To run this project from zero, you would execute these commands in order:

Create the Secret:
kubectl apply -f db-secret.yaml

Create the Pod:
kubectl apply -f sec-pod.yaml

Verify the output:
kubectl logs my-pod-secret-mount
